<|im_content> <|listOfContents><|pagenumber>1</|pagenumber></|listOfContents><|body><|h2><|center>3D Printing of the Neurovascular Bundle in the Temporomandibular Joint: A Human Cadaver Study</|center><|p><|a id="t00661"><|p>Aims and Objectives<|p>The aim is to investigate whether 3D printing methods can be applied for the production of a model of the neurovascular bundle (NVB) in the temporomandibular joint (TMJ).</|p><|b id="t00661b"><|p>Materials and Methods<|p><|a id="t00672"><|p>The NVB was dissected from 5 cadavers in the TMJ region. The specimens were then scanned by a computed tomography (CT) scan, and the data was processed using 3D printing methods for production of anatomical models of the NVB. The CT-scan images were converted into stereolithographic format (.stl), which is compatible with most 3D printers. The specimens' NVB was isolated from the TMJ region and then scanned using a high definition CT (HDCT) machine. The images of the NVB were then processed in order to produce anatomical models for printing by using a 3D printer. The original HDCT images were also printed by using a 3D printer.</|p><|b id="t00672b"><|p>Results<|p>The 3D printing process of the NVB was successful and the anatomical models can be used for surgical training, educational purposes, or research studies. The 3D printed specimens were able to reproduce the anatomy of the TMJ region in a realistic manner. With the aid of this model, it would be possible to practice TMJ surgeries and also to study tissues from cadavers.</|p><|b id="t00672c"><|p>Conclusions<|p>This work has shown that 3D printing methods are successful in the production of anatomical models for surgical training, educational purposes, or research studies. The 3D printed specimens were able to reproduce the anatomy of the TMJ region in a realistic manner.</|p><|b id="t00672d"><|p>Keywords<|p>temporomandibular joint; neurovascular bundle; 3D printing</|p></|a id="t00672e"><|p>
Introduction<|p>The temporomandibular joint (TMJ) is made up of the articular disc between the mandible and temporal bones, together with the surrounding muscles, ligaments, synovial capsule, and blood vessels. It is a complex anatomical structure that can be damaged by trauma or overuse from bruxism, which leads to internal derangements of the joints. These, in turn, can lead to disorders such as arthralgia, myalgia, temporalis muscle hypertrophy, and chronic pain (1). Reconstructive surgery has been used for these cases with good results (2), but it is not always easy due to the complex anatomy of this region. The neurovascular bundle (NVB) in the TMJ region is made up of the external carotid artery, internal carotid artery, and adjacent branches that go directly into the joint capsule and are surrounded by the periosteum of the temporal bone and the temporalis muscle. This study aims to produce anatomical models for surgery using 3D printing methods as well as to evaluate the feasibility of such a model in the TMJ region. </|p><|b id="t00672e1"><|p>Materials and Methods<|p>The cadaveric specimens were obtained from the Department of Anatomy, Faculty of Medicine Vajira Hospital, Navamindradhiraj University, Bangkok, Thailand. The study was approved by the Ethics Committee in Human Research (COA no. 142-58). The NVB was dissected from each specimen and then scanned by a high definition computed tomography (HDCT) machine (Philips Brilliance 16-slice; Philips Medical Systems, Best, Netherlands), with a slice thickness of 0.5 mm. The images were converted into stereolithographic format (.stl) using Mimics software version 17 (Materialise NV, Leuven, Belgium). These .stl files were then processed in order to produce anatomical models for printing by using a 3D printer (Stratasys Objet Eden 260VS; Stratasys Ltd., Eden Prairie, MN, USA) (Figure 1). The original HDCT images were also printed by using the same 3D printer. Conversion of the .stl files to a stereolithographic format (.stl) was performed in order to obtain the anatomical models for printing with this particular type of 3D printer (Figure 2). The original HDCT images were also printed by using the same machine.
The anatomical models and printed specimens were then evaluated for their accuracy, realism, and feasibility in surgery by a team of maxillofacial surgeons who practice TMJ surgery at Vajira Hospital. The team consisted of 3 consultants and one specialist who had attended various learning courses on the subject. They were asked to score each specimen on a scale from 1 (very poor) to 5 (excellent), with 3 being an average score. The scores were compared in order to determine which type of specimens produced the most realistic and accurate models for surgical training, educational purposes, or research studies.
<|p><|b id="t00672e1a"><|p>Results<|p>The 3D printed anatomical models were found to be more realistic (Figure 3) than the original HDCT images (Figure 4). The average score for the anatomical models was 3.8, while that of the original HDCT images was 2.75. The results showed a significant difference in accuracy between these two types of specimens (p < .01).
<|p><|b id="t00672e1c"><|p>Discussion<|p>The study has shown that the NVB can be reconstructed using 3D printing methods. The anatomical model was found to be more realistic than the original HDCT images, which also makes it a good tool for surgical training, educational purposes, or research studies (1).
